               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-174" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-174" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-174" type="surname" value="LING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-174" type="given" value="CHARLES ALFRED"></interp>CHARLES ALFRED LING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the son of Charles Ling, of the Commercial-road. On the 15th of Nov. the prisoner came into the shop to buy some fringe—I saw her take a length of ribbon out of a basket on the counter, and conceal it under her cloak—she went on talking to the young man who was serving her—I went to her in about five minutes, and accused her of having a piece of ribbon—she denied it several times—I threw her cloak aside, and saw it in her hand—she said she had no intention of taking it, nor was she aware she had it—my father took it from her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did she purchase anything? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, some fringe—she did not pay for it—she had not been looking at ribbons—there were five or six shopmen, but no other customers—he hap<lb></lb>peared confused.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-175" type="witnessName">
